parece que usan el double labelled water method (DLW) para medir el consumo energético de forma no invasiva administrando 2 isótopos de agua que dan indicación de las reacciones producidas con el dióxido decarbono o algo así. Es decir que se pueden usar para medir la combustión a lo largo del tiempo en el cuerpo

page 277: EVIDENCE CONSIDERED FOR ESTIMATING THE AVERAGE REQUIREMENT FOR CARBOHYDRATE

The minimal amount of carbohydrate required, either from endogenous
or exogenous sources, is determined by the brain’s requirement for glucose.
The brain is the only true carbohydrate-dependent organ in that it oxidizes
glucose completely to carbon dioxide and water. Normally, the brain uses
glucose almost exclusively for its energy needs. The endogenous glucose
production rate in a postabsorptive state correlates very well with the esti-
mated size of the brain from birth to adult life. However, not all of the
glucose produced is utilized by the brain (Bier et al., 1977; Felig, 1973).
BB:
- Bier DM, Leake RD, Haymond MW, Arnold KJ, Gruenke LD, Sperling MA, Kipnis
DM. 1977. Measurement of “true” glucose production rates in infancy and
childhood with 6,6-dideuteroglucose. Diabetes 26:1016–1023. --> FREE!!!
- Felig P. 1973. The glucose-alanine cycle. Metabolism 22:179–207. <-- PAYWALL over 25 dollars

The requirement for glucose has been reported to be approximately 110
to 140 g/d in adults (Cahill et al., 1968).
BB: Cahill GF, Owen OE, Morgan AP. 1968. The consumption of fuels during pro-
longed starvation. Adv Enzyme Reg 6:143–150. <-- PAYWALL over 50 dollars

